You got the right intuition! When you move a type like `String`, which implements `Drop` (automatically cleans up memory), Rust won’t let you access or use that variable after it’s moved. This is by design to prevent dangling pointers and double frees.

The fix? You can clone `s1` instead of moving it, so both variables have ownership:

```rust
fn main() {
  let s1 = String::from("hello");
  let s2 = s1.clone(); // Clone s1 before moving it!

  println!("s1: {}", s1);
}
```
This way, `s2` owns a copy of the string, leaving `s1` intact.

You have two options here. One is to create an owned copy of the string before borrowing it:

```rust
fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    let t = s.clone(); // Creates a deep copy
    println!("{}", t);
}
```
Or if you want to keep the original ownership and only pass around references, make sure you're using immutable borrowing correctly:

That’s one way. You can instead borrow everything your closure needs:

```rust
fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    let t = &s;
    let f = move || println!("{}", *t);
}
```
Note the `move` keyword here. But remember, using a closure with `move` takes ownership of all captured variables.
